        />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #a9a7af">
            <i>
              The Crimean Tatars are a Turkic ethnic group from the Crimean
              Peninsula, by the Black Sea. Credits: Center for European Policy
              Analysis
            </i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The what:</strong> The Crimean Tatar language is spoken by
            only around 100,000 people in Crimea, and UNESCO classifies it as
            severely endangered (meaning it is spoken mostly by grandparents and
            older generations, while parents may understand it but no longer
            pass it on to their children). The language is central to the
            identity of Crimean Tatars, the peninsulaâ€™s Indigenous population,
            and links to their Turkic roots (<a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-2-aug-25--h1-1-full-list-of-endangered-languages?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >full list of endangered languages</a
            >).
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The struggle:</strong> The language has survived mass
            deportations under Stalin and decades of assimilation. Since Russia
            annexed Crimea in 2014, Crimean Tatar language education has been
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-2-aug-25--h1-2-severely-restricted?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >severely restricted</a
            >. The number of schools teaching in Tatar fell from 384 to just
            119. Families asking for Tatar-language classes are often turned
            away or encouraged to choose Russian instead.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; filter: blur(5px)">
            <strong>The revival:</strong> Ukraine has expanded its support for
            the language, especially since 2022, when the war with Russia
            started. New university programs in Tatar philology have been
            launched, and a national language commission was created. In 2021,
            Ukraine officially adopted a Latin-based alphabet for Crimean Tatar,
            aligning it with other Turkic languages.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
